qas.question: What are some examples of philosophical physicalism?

answers.text: spacetime, physical energies and forces, dark matter

qas.question: Some people consider physicalism to be synonymous with what?

plausible_answers.text: the view that all that exists is ultimately physical

qas.question: What is the definition of non-physicalism?

plausible_answers.text: the view that all that exists is ultimately physical

qas.question: What is the definition of non-materialism?
What term is not preferred over materialism?

context: <a1_0>Materialism<a1_0/> is closely related to physicalism, <b2_0><b3_0>the view that all that exists is ultimately physical<b3_0/><b2_0/>. <b4_0>Philosophical physicalism<b4_0/> has evolved from materialism with the discoveries of the physical sciences to incorporate more sophisticated notions of physicality than mere ordinary matter, such as: <a0_0>spacetime, physical energies and forces, dark matter<a0_0/>, and so on. Thus the term "<b5_0>physicalism<b5_0/>" is preferred over "materialism" by some, while others use the terms as if they are synonymous.
